The Constitution is a contract. The branches are counterparties to each other. The states are counterparties. The people are counterparties. Jointly and severally.

No contract, no matter how brilliantly designed, can adequately guard against counterparty risk. You can spend months perfecting every clause, every contingency, every remedy. But if your counterparties act in bad faith‚Äîor simply refuse to perform‚Äîthe document becomes words on parchment and nothing more.

John Adams understood this. He wrote: "Our Constitution was made only for a moral and religious People. It is wholly inadequate to the government of any other."

The founders designed checks and balances, separation of powers, federalism, staggered elections‚Äîall to make coordinated capture difficult. Madison's theory was elegant: "Ambition must be made to counteract ambition. The interest of the man must be connected with the constitutional rights of the place."
The assumption was that a senator's ambition would be channeled through the Senate. A representative's through the House. A judge's through the judiciary. Each officeholder would defend their institution's prerogatives because their personal power derived from institutional power. The branches would compete because competition served self-interest.

It was elegant game theory. Create a structure where self-interest produces public benefit. Don't rely on virtue alone‚Äîharness ambition itself.

But Madison may not have adequately planned for ambition to be both personal and tribal. Tribal more than institutional. That ambition might prosper more by colluding than competing.

If a senator's power, reelection, and future depend more on loyalty to party or leader than on defending the Senate as an institution, the incentives flip. Institutional competition becomes costly. Tribal collusion becomes rational.

Why would a senator challenge a president of their own party? It angers the base, invites a primary challenge, cuts off donor money, ends careers. The personal interest of the man is no longer connected to the constitutional rights of the place. It's connected to the tribe.

The branches stop checking each other. The party in power captures multiple branches and operates them in coordination. The competition isn't between branches anymore‚Äîit's between tribes, with the branches as captured instruments.

Madison designed for institutional rivalry. He got partisan cartel behavior.

In game theory terms, Madison assumed a competitive game where each player maximizes by defending their position. But if players form coalitions and share spoils, cooperation dominates competition. The branches collude rather than check.

And it's not just party‚Äîit's tribal identity. The bond isn't merely transactional. It's identity-based. Tribal loyalty triggers different psychology than institutional loyalty. More visceral. More resistant to persuasion. More willing to tolerate norm violations by the in-group.

When politics becomes tribal, the other side isn't a legitimate competitor‚Äîthey're an existential threat. Any means of defeating them becomes justified. Defending institutional norms that constrain your own side becomes betrayal.

Madison worried endlessly about faction. His solution was the extended republic‚Äîso many factions that none could dominate. But he may not have anticipated binary sorting. Two mega-factions that subsume all others and capture the branches themselves. The multiplicity of factions was supposed to prevent coordination. A two-party system with tribal characteristics enables it.

The payoff matrix now favors collusion overwhelmingly. Madison's design assumed defection from tribal loyalty would be rewarded by institutional gain. It isn't. Not anymore.

Political parties now act only as an imperfect check on each other. Elections have become winner-take-all struggles for control over government‚Äîcontests for dominion where the prize is near-absolute power until the next battle. The winner governs; the loser opposes. Neither party checks itself. Neither respects limits when in power. Each seeks total control.

This fulfills Madison's own definition of tyranny. In Federalist 47, he wrote: "The accumulation of all powers, legislative, executive, and judiciary, in the same hands, whether of one, a few, or many, and whether hereditary, self-appointed, or elective, may justly be pronounced the very definition of tyranny."
We have achieved exactly that‚Äîrotating tyranny, elective tyranny, tribal tyranny. The forms of the republic remain. The reality is control, alternating between factions that recognize no limits when they hold power and no legitimacy when they don't.

The system is resilient to isolated failures. It is not resilient to correlated failures. When the counterparties align in bad faith, there is no external backstop. No fourth branch. No deus ex machina.
When Madison's game theory fails‚Äîwhen ambition colludes rather than competes, when tribes capture institutions, when the branches fall in line, when elections become contests for temporary absolutism‚Äîwhat's left?

We are back to where we started. The only real guarantee, the only true collateral, is the virtue of the people.

But virtue isn't passive. It requires action. It means refusing to comply with unjust orders. Speaking out when silence is safer. Protecting the vulnerable. Bearing witness. And when called to serve, it means one thing more.

There remains one check that cannot be appealed, overruled, or stayed pending review: the jury.
Every other check requires collective action or institutional will. This one requires only conscience.
Jury nullification has a long history‚Äîone deliberately obscured. But the power is real. A verdict of not guilty cannot be appealed. Jurors cannot be punished for their decision.

In 1670, English jurors refused to convict William Penn for preaching Quakerism. The judge imprisoned them. A higher court freed them, establishing that jurors cannot be punished for their verdicts.

In 1735, a New York jury acquitted John Peter Zenger of seditious libel though he'd clearly published criticisms of the royal governor. They rejected the unjust law. A landmark for press freedom‚Äîachieved through nullification.

Northern juries repeatedly refused to convict those who aided escaped slaves under the Fugitive Slave Act. They understood compliance would make them complicit in evil.

John Adams wrote that it is not only the juror's right "but his duty... to find the verdict according to his own best understanding, judgment, and conscience, though in direct opposition to the direction of the court."

The jury was designed as the conscience of the community inserted directly into the legal process. The last democratic check. The final counterparty.

Modern courts suppress this knowledge. Judges instruct juries to follow the law as given. The system depends on juror ignorance of their own authority.
But the power remains.

When law and justice diverge‚Äîwhen the machinery of the state perpetrates injustice‚Äîcitizens have not just the right but perhaps the obligation to refuse complicity.

One person, seated in a jury box, can say: Not in my name. I will not convict.

If the Constitution's ultimate collateral is the virtue of the people, jury nullification is that virtue made operational. My conscience is not subordinate to the state's commands.

We started with virtue. We end with virtue. Madison's machinery was meant to reduce our dependence on it. But when the machinery is captured, when ambition colludes instead of competes, when tribes override institutions, when elections become winner-take-all contests for dominion, the elaborate design falls away and we are left with the original question.

Are we virtuous? Will we act?

Franklin, asked what kind of government the Convention had created, answered: "A republic, if you can keep it."

The founders bet on us. The document was the terms. We are the counterparty.

The question is whether we'll perform‚Äîor default.
